      "title": "Use the y-intercept definition",
      "content": "The $y$-intercept of $y = f(x)$ is the point where $x = 0$, i.e., $\\bigl(0,\\, f(0)\\bigr)$."
    },
    {
      "title": "Evaluate f(0)",
      "content": "$$f(0) = 3(0) - \\frac{1}{4} = -\\frac{1}{4}$$<br/>So the $y$-intercept is $\\left(0,\\, -\\dfrac{1}{4}\\right)$.<br/><br/><strong>A</strong> is correct."
    }
  ]
}
